1
00:00:00,740 --> 00:00:01,740
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,740 --> 00:00:03,150
The Journey Begins

3
00:00:03,150 --> 00:00:12,800
The wonderful views of snow-topped mountains
passed unnoticed as the train sped away from

4
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:15,009
Syria towards Istanbul.

5
00:00:15,009 --> 00:00:22,849
As the Belgian detective M. Hercule Poirot
drank his coffee, he watched the only other

6
00:00:22,849 --> 00:00:29,779
person in the restaurant carriage - a tall,
thin young lady, perhaps twenty-eight years

7
00:00:29,779 --> 00:00:30,779
old.

8
00:00:30,779 --> 00:00:37,430
From the way that she ate her breakfast, she
seemed to be an experienced and confident

9
00:00:37,430 --> 00:00:38,430
traveller.

10
00:00:38,430 --> 00:00:45,040
He admired her pale face, tidy dark hair and
cool grey eyes.

11
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:52,710
A good-looking woman, he thought, but perhaps
a little too cold and efficient to be described

12
00:00:52,710 --> 00:00:53,710
as pretty.

13
00:00:53,710 --> 00:00:59,650
Soon a tall, thin man entered the restaurant
carriage.

14
00:00:59,650 --> 00:01:06,860
He was between forty and fifty, with greying
hair and skin darkened by the sun.

15
00:01:06,860 --> 00:01:09,759
He spoke to the woman.

16
00:01:09,759 --> 00:01:11,840
His accent was English.

17
00:01:11,840 --> 00:01:14,580
'Morning, Miss Debenham.'

18
00:01:14,580 --> 00:01:18,869
'Good morning, Colonel Arbuthnot,' she replied.

19
00:01:18,869 --> 00:01:23,520
'Do you mind if I sit with you?'

20
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:25,270
'Of course not.

21
00:01:25,270 --> 00:01:26,439
Please, sit.'

22
00:01:26,439 --> 00:01:28,090
She smiled politely.

23
00:01:28,090 --> 00:01:32,000
He sat down and ordered his breakfast.

24
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:40,979
He looked quickly towards M. Poirot - at his
enormous, curled moustache and strange, egg-shaped

25
00:01:40,979 --> 00:01:43,369
head - then looked away.

26
00:01:43,369 --> 00:01:49,649
'Just a silly looking foreigner,' he thought
to himself.

27
00:01:49,649 --> 00:01:56,909
The British pair exchanged a few polite words
over their breakfast, and at lunchtime they

28
00:01:56,909 --> 00:01:58,280
sat together again.

29
00:01:58,280 --> 00:02:05,789
The man spoke of his life in the army in India,
and occasionally asked the girl questions

30
00:02:05,789 --> 00:02:08,920
about Baghdad, where she had been a governess.

31
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:17,920
When they discovered that they had some friends
in common, they became more friendly.

32
00:02:17,920 --> 00:02:21,470
'Are you stopping in Istanbul?'

33
00:02:21,470 --> 00:02:22,470
the man asked.

34
00:02:22,470 --> 00:02:23,470
'No, I'm going straight through.

35
00:02:23,470 --> 00:02:27,610
I saw all the sights two years ago, on my
way to Baghdad.'

36
00:02:27,610 --> 00:02:31,920
'Well, I must say I'm very glad about that.

37
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:34,780
I'm going straight through too.'

38
00:02:34,780 --> 00:02:37,450
His face went a little red.

39
00:02:37,450 --> 00:02:42,410
'That will be nice,' said Miss Debenham without
emotion.

40
00:02:42,410 --> 00:02:46,750
The train stopped late that evening at Konya.

41
00:02:46,750 --> 00:02:52,190
The two English travellers went outside for
some fresh air and exercise.

42
00:02:52,190 --> 00:02:59,320
After a few minutes, Poirot decided to get
some air too, and started to walk along the

43
00:02:59,320 --> 00:03:00,350
platform.

44
00:03:00,350 --> 00:03:02,920
It was bitterly cold.

45
00:03:02,920 --> 00:03:08,470
Out of the darkness, he heard two voices.

46
00:03:08,470 --> 00:03:10,550
Arbuthnot was speaking.

47
00:03:10,550 --> 00:03:11,610
'Mary -'

48
00:03:11,610 --> 00:03:14,900
A girl interrupted him.

49
00:03:14,900 --> 00:03:16,730
'Not now.

50
00:03:16,730 --> 00:03:18,430
Not now.

51
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:19,790
When it's all over.

52
00:03:19,790 --> 00:03:22,880
When it's behind us - then -

53
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:28,400
M. Poirot silently changed direction.

54
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:31,530
'Strange,' he said to himself.

55
00:03:31,530 --> 00:03:38,090
It was the voice of Miss Debenham, but a very
different one from the cool, efficient voice

56
00:03:38,090 --> 00:03:40,380
that he had heard on the train.

57
00:03:40,380 --> 00:03:46,040
The next afternoon, the train stopped unexpectedly.

58
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:50,080
Poirot asked the conductor if there was a
problem.

59
00:03:50,080 --> 00:03:53,090
Miss Debenham was just behind him.

60
00:03:53,090 --> 00:03:55,760
'What's the matter?'

61
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:57,790
she asked Poirot in French.

62
00:03:57,790 --> 00:04:01,390
'Why are we stopping?'

63
00:04:01,390 --> 00:04:08,600
'Something caught fire under the restaurant
carriage,' he explained, 'but they are repairing

64
00:04:08,600 --> 00:04:09,600
the damage.

65
00:04:09,600 --> 00:04:13,540
It is nothing serious.'

66
00:04:13,540 --> 00:04:16,980
She looked impatient.

67
00:04:16,980 --> 00:04:20,410
'But the time!

68
00:04:20,410 --> 00:04:21,709
This will delay us.'

69
00:04:21,709 --> 00:04:23,650
'It is possible - yes,' agreed Poirot.

70
00:04:23,650 --> 00:04:26,370
'But we can't afford delay!

71
00:04:26,370 --> 00:04:35,120
If we are delayed by more than an hour, we
will miss our connection with the Orient Express.'

72
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:37,439
Her hands were shaking.

73
00:04:37,439 --> 00:04:39,360
She was clearly very upset.

74
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:43,849
Luckily, her worries were soon forgotten.

75
00:04:43,849 --> 00:04:51,110
Ten minutes later the train was again on its
way, and the rest of the journey to Istanbul

76
00:04:51,110 --> 00:04:54,389
went very smoothly.

77
00:04:54,389 --> 00:04:58,930
M. Poirot went straight to the Tokatlian Hotel.

78
00:04:58,930 --> 00:05:05,979
He was looking forward to a few days visiting
the sights in Istanbul before he continued

79
00:05:05,979 --> 00:05:10,909
his journey home.

80
00:05:10,909 --> 00:05:12,060
At the hotel, he asked if he had any letters.

81
00:05:12,060 --> 00:05:16,620
There were three, and an urgent message too.

82
00:05:16,620 --> 00:05:20,219
This was a surprise.

83
00:05:20,219 --> 00:05:24,620
'Unexpected change in Kassner case.

84
00:05:24,620 --> 00:05:29,900
Please return immediately,' he read.

85
00:05:29,900 --> 00:05:33,199
'How annoying!' he said to himself.

86
00:05:33,199 --> 00:05:35,509
He looked at the clock.

87
00:05:35,509 --> 00:05:42,580
'I must leave Istanbul tonight,' he told the
man at the hotel desk.

88
00:05:42,580 --> 00:05:47,509
'Can you get me a first-class compartment
to London?'

89
00:05:47,509 --> 00:05:49,189
'Of course, Monsieur.

90
00:05:49,189 --> 00:05:53,680
The train is almost empty in the winter.

91
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:55,449
It leaves at nine o'clock.'

92
00:05:55,449 --> 00:05:59,370
'Thank you,' said M. Poirot.

93
00:05:59,370 --> 00:06:02,620
He had just enough time for some dinner.

94
00:06:02,620 --> 00:06:09,990
As he was ordering his food in the hotel restaurant,
he felt a hand on his shoulder.

95
00:06:09,990 --> 00:06:12,110
'M. Poirot!

96
00:06:12,110 --> 00:06:17,879
What an unexpected pleasure!' said a voice
behind him.

97
00:06:17,879 --> 00:06:22,409
The speaker was a short, fat man in his fifties.

98
00:06:22,409 --> 00:06:25,050
'M. Bouc!'

99
00:06:25,050 --> 00:06:26,620
cried Poirot.

100
00:06:26,620 --> 00:06:33,719
M. Bouc was Belgian, and had a high position
in the Compagnie Internationale des Wagons

101
00:06:33,719 --> 00:06:34,719
Lits.

102
00:06:34,719 --> 00:06:42,150
The two men had been friends for many years,
since the days when Poirot was a young detective

103
00:06:42,150 --> 00:06:44,229
in the Belgian police force.

104
00:06:44,229 --> 00:06:51,740
'You are very far from home, my friend,' said
M. Bouc.

105
00:06:51,740 --> 00:06:52,740
'Yes.

106
00:06:52,740 --> 00:06:55,839
A little business in Syria.

107
00:06:55,839 --> 00:07:00,889
But I am heading home tonight - on the Orient
Express, if there is a compartment.'

108
00:07:00,889 --> 00:07:01,889
'Excellent!

109
00:07:01,889 --> 00:07:05,960
I will be on the same train.

110
00:07:05,960 --> 00:07:11,219
Later, you can tell me all your news.

111
00:07:11,219 --> 00:07:15,949
You are a famous detective now, I hear.'

112
00:07:15,949 --> 00:07:22,409
With a warm smile, M. Bouc left the restaurant.

113
00:07:22,409 --> 00:07:28,529
M. Poirot returned to the job of keeping his
moustache out of the soup.

114
00:07:28,529 --> 00:07:34,379
Soon, though, his attention was caught by
two men who were sitting together at a table

115
00:07:34,379 --> 00:07:37,339
not far from his.

116
00:07:37,339 --> 00:07:42,050
The younger was a friendly-looking man of
thirty, clearly an American.

117
00:07:42,050 --> 00:07:48,699
The other was in his sixties and seemed at
first to be a kind old gentleman.

118
00:07:48,699 --> 00:07:57,289
But when his small, shadowy eyes met Poirot's,
the detective's opinion of him changed completely.

119
00:07:57,289 --> 00:08:03,219
Just for a second Poirot sensed that the man
was dangerous.

120
00:08:03,219 --> 00:08:10,150
It seemed that there was a wild animal hidden
inside the man's body, looking out at the

121
00:08:10,150 --> 00:08:13,599
world with those evil eyes.

122
00:08:13,599 --> 00:08:19,970
M. Poirot soon joined his friend M. Bouc near
the hotel desk.

123
00:08:19,970 --> 00:08:26,449
Their conversation was interrupted by the
hotel worker who was organising M. Poirot's

124
00:08:26,449 --> 00:08:27,509
train ticket.

125
00:08:27,509 --> 00:08:31,080
'It is very strange, Monsieur.

126
00:08:31,080 --> 00:08:37,039
All the first-class compartments are booked
- and the second-class too.'

127
00:08:37,039 --> 00:08:40,120
'What?' asked M. Bouc.

128
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:43,969
'At this time of year?

129
00:08:43,969 --> 00:08:44,969
Impossible!'

130
00:08:44,969 --> 00:08:48,839
'But it is true, sir,' the man replied.

131
00:08:48,839 --> 00:08:51,490
'I am sorry.'

132
00:08:51,490 --> 00:08:57,199
'Well, well,' M. Bouc said to Poirot, 'do
not worry.

133
00:08:57,199 --> 00:09:01,810
We will arrange something with the conductor.'

134
00:09:01,810 --> 00:09:04,800
He looked up at the clock.

135
00:09:04,800 --> 00:09:10,120
'Come,' he said, 'it is time to go.'

136
00:09:10,120 --> 00:09:15,060
At the station, M. Bouc took the conductor
to one side.

137
00:09:15,060 --> 00:09:20,279
'We must find a compartment for this gentleman
here.

138
00:09:20,279 --> 00:09:23,760
He is a friend of mine.'

139
00:09:23,760 --> 00:09:27,279
'But we are completely full, Monsieur.

140
00:09:27,279 --> 00:09:29,820
It is most unusual.'

141
00:09:29,820 --> 00:09:38,250
'Well,' said M. Bouc, 'tomorrow there will
be more compartments, when we reach Belgrade.

142
00:09:38,250 --> 00:09:41,339
The problem is for tonight.'

143
00:09:41,339 --> 00:09:44,130
He paused for a moment.

144
00:09:44,130 --> 00:09:47,259
'Everyone has arrived?'

145
00:09:47,259 --> 00:09:50,860
The conductor looked at his list.

146
00:09:50,860 --> 00:09:54,810
'Number 7 - a second-class compartment.

147
00:09:54,810 --> 00:10:18,180
The gentleman - a Mr Harris - has not yet
come, and it is four minutes to nine.'

148
00:10:18,180 --> 00:10:19,500
'Then put M. Poirot's luggage in number 7,'
said M. Bouc.

149
00:10:19,500 --> 00:10:21,180
'If this Mr Harris arrives, we will tell him
that he is too late.'

150
00:10:21,180 --> 00:10:26,050
With words of thanks to M. Bouc, Poirot followed
his luggage to compartment 7.

151
00:10:26,050 --> 00:10:31,490
Inside it was the tall young American from
the hotel.

152
00:10:31,490 --> 00:10:35,310
He was not pleased when Poirot entered.

153
00:10:35,310 --> 00:10:38,850
'Excuse me,' he said in French.

154
00:10:38,850 --> 00:10:43,029
'I think you've made a mistake.'

155
00:10:43,029 --> 00:10:52,089
'There are no other beds on the train, M.
MacQueen,' the conductor apologised.

156
00:10:52,089 --> 00:10:54,240
'The gentleman has to come in here.'

157
00:10:54,240 --> 00:10:59,529
Poirot noticed that the conductor seemed almost
as annoyed as the American.

158
00:10:59,529 --> 00:11:02,890
Perhaps he had been offered money to keep
the other bed empty.

159
00:11:02,890 --> 00:11:09,250
When the conductor had left, MacQueen's annoyance
seemed forgotten.

160
00:11:09,250 --> 00:11:15,139
'The train's surprisingly full,' he said with
a smile.

161
00:11:15,139 --> 00:11:18,800
Just then, the train started moving.

162
00:11:18,800 --> 00:11:22,839
Their three-day journey across Europe had
begun.

163
00:11:22,839 --> 00:11:33,050
After a good night's sleep, Poirot spent the
morning alone in his compartment, looking

164
00:11:33,050 --> 00:11:36,540
at his notes on the case that had called him
to London.

165
00:11:36,540 --> 00:11:40,959
He had a late lunch with M. Bouc.

166
00:11:40,959 --> 00:11:46,620
As they relaxed at the end of the meal, they
looked around the restaurant carriage.

167
00:11:46,620 --> 00:11:53,850
'If I were a writer, I would use this scene,'
said M. Bouc.

168
00:11:53,850 --> 00:12:02,339
'All around us are people of all classes,
of all nationalities, of all ages.

169
00:12:02,339 --> 00:12:08,139
For three days these people sleep and eat
under one roof.

170
00:12:08,139 --> 00:12:09,940
They cannot escape each other.

171
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:22,480
But at the end of the three days they go their
separate ways and never see each other again.'

172
00:12:22,480 --> 00:12:29,790
There were thirteen people in the restaurant
carriage, and M. Bouc was right: they were

173
00:12:29,790 --> 00:12:31,709
a very mixed group.

174
00:12:31,709 --> 00:12:39,860
A big, hairy Italian was sitting with a thin,
pale Englishman, probably a servant, and an

175
00:12:39,860 --> 00:12:42,410
American in a brightly-coloured suit.

176
00:12:42,410 --> 00:12:49,670
The American and Italian exchanged business
advice while the Englishman stared out of

177
00:12:49,670 --> 00:12:50,750
the window.

178
00:12:50,750 --> 00:12:54,769
He was clearly not enjoying the conversation.

179
00:12:54,769 --> 00:13:02,920
At the next table sat an ugly lady whose clothes
and jewellery, though they did nothing to

180
00:13:02,920 --> 00:13:09,129
help her appearance, were clearly from the
most expensive shops in Paris.

181
00:13:09,129 --> 00:13:11,600
'That is Princess Dragomiroff,' said M. Bouc.

182
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:22,860
'She is Russian, but her husband got his money
out of the country before the Communists took

183
00:13:22,860 --> 00:13:23,860
control.

184
00:13:23,860 --> 00:13:28,800
So ugly, but what a character!'

185
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:36,180
At another table, Mary Debenham was sitting
with a kind looking middle-aged woman with

186
00:13:36,180 --> 00:13:44,110
fair hair and a sheep-like face; with them
was an older woman, an American who never

187
00:13:44,110 --> 00:13:46,600
seemed to stop talking.

188
00:13:46,600 --> 00:13:50,660
Colonel Arbuthnot was at the next table, alone.

189
00:13:50,660 --> 00:13:57,490
Against the wall sat a middle-aged woman dressed
in black - a servant, Poirot guessed.

190
00:13:57,490 --> 00:14:04,649
Then there was a good-looking man of about
thirty with a beautiful young woman.

191
00:14:04,649 --> 00:14:12,420
Perfectly dressed in the latest fashion, she
had pale skin and large brown eyes.

192
00:14:12,420 --> 00:14:15,360
Poirot could not take his eyes off her.

193
00:14:15,360 --> 00:14:24,980
'A Hungarian diplomat and his wife, I believe,'
said M. Bouc, seeing his friend's interest.

194
00:14:24,980 --> 00:14:27,639
'A very attractive couple.'

195
00:14:27,639 --> 00:14:35,259
Then there was MacQueen and his employer,
the man with the kind face and the small,

196
00:14:35,259 --> 00:14:36,320
cruel eyes.

197
00:14:36,320 --> 00:14:42,959
M. Bouc returned to his compartment while
M. Poirot finished his coffee.

198
00:14:42,959 --> 00:14:51,029
'My daughter said I would have no trouble
with these food tickets,' he heard the American

199
00:14:51,029 --> 00:14:54,399
woman say to Miss Debenham as she paid the
waiter.

200
00:14:54,399 --> 00:15:00,910
'But then there's money for the waiter, and
that bottle of water.

201
00:15:00,910 --> 00:15:02,389
Nasty water too.

202
00:15:02,389 --> 00:15:09,930
They haven't got any Evian, which seems very
odd to me.'

203
00:15:09,930 --> 00:15:12,710
She looked crossly at the coins in front of
her.

204
00:15:12,710 --> 00:15:18,610
'And look at this rubbish that the waiter's
given me.

205
00:15:18,610 --> 00:15:20,380
Dinars or something.

206
00:15:20,380 --> 00:15:22,150
My daughter said -'

207
00:15:22,150 --> 00:15:28,029
At this point, Mary Debenham made a polite
excuse and left the table.

208
00:15:28,029 --> 00:15:31,600
Colonel Arbuthnot got up and followed her.

209
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:41,460
Very soon the restaurant carriage was empty
except for Poirot and MacQueen's employer.

210
00:15:41,460 --> 00:15:46,319
To the detective's surprise, the man came
and sat down at his table.

211
00:15:46,319 --> 00:15:52,040
'Good afternoon,' he said in a quiet, deep
voice.

212
00:15:52,040 --> 00:15:54,860
'My name is Ratchett.

213
00:15:54,860 --> 00:16:00,180
I think that I have the pleasure of speaking
to Mr Hercule Poirot.

214
00:16:00,180 --> 00:16:02,240
Is that right?'

215
00:16:02,240 --> 00:16:07,959
'Your information is correct, Monsieur,' said
the detective.

216
00:16:07,959 --> 00:16:13,749
'I want you to do a job for me,' said Ratchett.

217
00:16:13,749 --> 00:16:16,290
Poirot looked surprised.

218
00:16:16,290 --> 00:16:20,720
'I take very few cases, I'm afraid.'

219
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:22,220
'Of course.

220
00:16:22,220 --> 00:16:27,959
But this, Mr Poirot, means money.

221
00:16:27,959 --> 00:16:30,459
Big money.'

222
00:16:30,459 --> 00:16:32,279
Poirot was silent for a moment.

223
00:16:32,279 --> 00:16:41,269
Then he said, 'What do you wish me to do for
you, M. - er - Ratchett?'

224
00:16:41,269 --> 00:16:47,600
'Mr Poirot, I am a rich man - a very rich
man.

225
00:16:47,600 --> 00:16:52,120
Men in my position have enemies.

226
00:16:52,120 --> 00:16:55,740
Someone has threatened to kill me.

227
00:16:55,740 --> 00:16:59,509
I can look after myself quite well.'

228
00:16:59,509 --> 00:17:03,579
He quickly showed Poirot the gun in his pocket.

229
00:17:03,579 --> 00:17:08,459
'But I'd like to be especially careful.

230
00:17:08,459 --> 00:17:14,679
Remember, we are talking big money, Mr Poirot.'

231
00:17:14,679 --> 00:17:17,910
Poirot thought for some minutes.

232
00:17:17,910 --> 00:17:24,930
Finally he said, 'I am sorry, Monsieur, but
I cannot help you.'

233
00:17:24,930 --> 00:17:27,150
The other man smiled.

234
00:17:27,150 --> 00:17:31,790
'Not even if I give you twenty thousand dollars?'

235
00:17:31,790 --> 00:17:32,850
'No, Monsieur.'

236
00:17:32,850 --> 00:17:34,430
'But why not?

237
00:17:34,430 --> 00:17:40,400
Why does this case not interest you?'

238
00:17:40,400 --> 00:17:43,650
Poirot stood up.

239
00:17:43,650 --> 00:17:53,830
'Forgive me for being personal, but I do not
like your face, M. Ratchett,' he said.

